üëâThe truth by @chroniclesofstrength

Truth is, we can‚Äôt decide where we lose our body fat. Everybody has their trouble spots, and for a lot of people, belly fat is a big one. So while you can‚Äôt spot reduce‚Äîdoing sit ups, crunches, etc, are useless for getting rid of stomach fat, so you can stop doing those, right now‚Äîyou CAN work to bring down your bodyfat overall.‚Ä®--‚Ä®-‚Ä®üëâHere‚Äôs what I recommend. Start by cleaning up your diet. Get rid of the sugar and processed food. Load up on fruits, veggies, lean protein, and lots of water. That‚Äôs step one. After that, focus on short, high intensity bouts of exercise. Use resistance training and metabolic conditioning. Also, do as much walking as you can. Brisk walking is one of the ultimate secret weapons for getting rid of stubborn fat, especially when done in conjunction with a higher intensity exercise regimen.‚Ä®--‚Ä®-‚Ä®‚òùÔ∏èStress and sleep are the other major factors. Belly fat is often referred to as ‚Äústress fat‚Äù for a reason. Poor sleep and an overly nervous or excited lifestyle can attribute to fat accumulation in your lower stomach, love handles, etc. So be sure to have a good sleep hygiene protocol and ways of relaxing throughout the day. Even just the occasional cat nap would be a good idea. ü§ßMeditation, too, can be quite beneficial. --‚Ä®-‚Ä®‚òùÔ∏èLastly, be patient. It‚Äôs always the trouble spots that take the longest to go away. They also tend to be the quickest to reappear. So commit to a process and be in for the long haul.‚Ä®--‚Ä®-‚Ä®Hope this helps. üí™Any questions, leave ‚Äòem below!‚Ä®--‚Ä®-‚Ä®Strong ON!

Top low calorie foods @smurray_32
‚ûñ
Today I want to touch upon the myth that is ‚ÄúNegative calorie foods‚Äù. The whole concept driving this claim is that you burn more kcals from digesting a certain food than the actual kcal within the food itself. This is also referred to as diet induced thermogensisis (DIT) which is defined as the increase in energy expenditure above basal fasting level divided by the energy content of the food ingested & commonly expressed as a percentage (Westerterp 2004).
‚ûñ
Reported DIT values for separate macros are 0-3% for fat, 5-10% for carbs, 20-30% for protein (Acheson 1993) thus if we take the average % for each macronutrient (1.5% for fat, 7.5% carbs & 25% protein) we can clearly work out that there are in fact no ‚Äúnegative calorie foods‚Äù.
‚ûñ
Example, celery, the most commonly claimed ‚Äúnegative calorie‚Äù food. 100g celery = ~17kcal, 3g carbs (12kcal), 0.7g protein (2.8kcal) & 0.2g fat (1.8kcal). Therefore, given DIT for the specific macros above, eat 17kcal of celery & you end up with a NET 13.763kcal. Equation used = 12(0.25) + 2.8(0.075) + 1.8(0.015) = 3.237kcal burned from DIT of that 17kcal.
‚ûñ
Not exactly negative is it? While I know I‚Äôm being extremely picky & that, in the grand scheme of things, 13kcal from celery should NOT be stressed out on, weighed or tracked,  it‚Äôs the concept I want to get through to you. 13kcal is not negative 13kcal. Eat 3000 ‚ÄúNET‚Äù kcal of celery with a maintenance of 2500kcal & you will still gain weight (Hill et al 2012). Furthermore, take celery again as the example. What do people, especially a typical ‚Äúmindless dieter‚Äù, do when they hear the claim that celery is ‚Äúnegative calories‚Äù? Start snacking on celery on its own or start snacking on it with peanut butter & Nutella which contain hundreds of kcals? The latter most likely. Another example ‚Äúspinach is negative kcals so let‚Äôs add it to my pizza‚Äù you get the point. When you ingest something other than water or any artificially modified kcal free products, there will always be energy (calories) in it. Some will have lots (icecream), some will have barely any & be negligible in th

Do you intermittent fast? ü§î by @smurray_32
‚ûñ
When compared to regular/continuous energy restriction, intermittent fasting (IF) has shown to result in ‚Äúapparently equivalent outcomes‚Äù in terms of body weight reduction & body composition change (Seimon et al 2015). This therefore supports the notion that, IF operates under one fundamental mechanism, sustaining a calorie deficit which, as we know is the one & only thing required in order to evoke fat loss (Hill et al 2012).
‚ûñ
So, IF is NOT magic as, all it does is create a calorie deficit by having you skip breakfast however, it is worthy to note that, IF has shown to be superior in aiding to reduce appetite (Scharrer 1999, Horn et al 2004) thus resulting in VOLUNATARY kcal reduction (Dutton et al 2011). Therefore, in addition to IF being able to create a calorie deficit (much like regular/continuous energy restriction), it can increase ADHERANCE to sustaining said deficit by reducing hunger however, if you can ADHERE to sustaining the same calorie deficit via regular/continuous energy restriction, then that seems just as good.
‚ûñ‚Ä®Conclusion: There is a HUGE range of dietary approaches which you can follow in order to lose fat (low-fat, low carb, keto, IF etc.) which can all be similarly effective for improving body composition, therefore, once adequate protein is consumed per day i.e. 1.6-3g/kg depending on your phase of training, bf% & caloric consumption (Helms et al 2013), the dietary approach & macronutrient composition (fat : carbs) you chose to implement should simply come down to the one that allows you to ADHERE easiest to consuming the caloric requirements required for achieving your goal (weight gain/loss).

It‚Äôs all about balance!‚†Ä
----‚†Ä
Guys, for some of you there may come a time when you feel like you‚Äôve tried all the diets...macro counting, cutting out carbs, cleanses, paleo, detoxes...and after a long time of trial and error, you finally realize that you need a less strict and more balanced approach to life. We‚Äôve been there too, and we came to quickly realize that the 80/20 rule is one of the best rules you can follow. Yes, the ‚Äúeat healthy 80% of the time, and treat-yo-self the other 20%‚Äù rule because it allows you to have a more realistic outlook in life.‚†Ä
If your favorite food in the üåéis burgers, and you are on a diet that never lets you within 50 feet of a bun, your happiness will be crushed. And while some people swear by the words ‚Äònothing tastes as good as skinny feels‚Äô, we beg to differ ‚Äì in our humble opinion, burgers taste as good as skinny feels.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
Remember, diets don‚Äôt have to be an either-or situation? If you focus on eating healthy 80% of the time, you can choose to indulge a bit for the other 20%, allowing yourself to nourish your body AND enjoy some of the finer things in life, like a Whopper with fries. üçîüçü‚†Ä
----‚†Ä

Do you eat your kid‚Äôs leftovers? Yes or no? by @calorieshealth
.
.
I get a lot of questions about what happens to the food that is leftover from making cute bentos. Or the food that my kids don't touch. Or the food that my kids only take one bite of. Nothing glamorous: I eat it. Or I put it in my hubby's lunch and make him eat it. üòÇ Let's just say, since having kids, it takes a lot more to gross me out than before. I mean, if the kid has already sneezed point blank in my face, then who cares if I eat the lunch he sneezed on? ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüôàüòú ‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
Eating their leftovers does prevent a lot of food waste. I think of it as taking one for the team so that they can learn to eat in a no-pressure environment.

Do you find dieting difficult? by @smurray_32
‚ûñ
ü•¶Protein fluff/cauliflower/watermelon: Studies have shown that high volume, low energy density foods will sig. decrease hunger & desire to eat (Latner et al 2008 & 2009). Therefore, foods such as melons, protein fluffs, cauliflower etc can be great additions to your diet/meals in order to add minimal extra kcals but a load more bulk to fill up your stomach
‚ûñ
ü•£Oats: Fibre has shown to have a positive influence on reducing caloric intake, again likely due to increasing satiation (Keenan et al 2006). Therefore oats, which, on average, contain nearly 12g/100g, or any other high fibre food for that matter can be great options for making a diet feel easier
‚ûñ
ü•îWhite potatoes: In a study by Holt et al (1995), results showed boiled potatoes to rank the highest in terms of satiation out of 38 different foods followed by oatmeal (another benefit of oats), oranges & brown pasta. Therefore, potatoes should be a staple carb source if you struggle with hunger
‚ûñ
üçóAny meat/fish/eggs etc: Protein is the most satiating & thermogenic macro thus drinks/foods high in protein can help keep you full, decrease appetite & burn more via digestion (Pesta  Samuel 2014, CrovettI et al 1998, Weigle et al 2005)
‚ûñ
ü•§Extras: For those on poverty macros, sugar free gums, syrups, sodas etc. can all also be of use to aid reducing kcal intake if used instead of more energy dense options.
‚Äî‚Äî

‚ûñ‚Ä®Conclusion: There is a HUGE range of dietary approaches which you can follow in order to lose fat (low-fat, low carb, keto, IF etc.) which can all be similarly effective for improving body composition, therefore, once adequate protein is consumed per day i.e. 1.6-3g/kg depending on your phase of training, bf% & caloric consumption (Helms et al 2013), the dietary approach & macronutrient composition (fat : carbs) you chose to implement should simply come down to the one that allows you to ADHERE easiest to consuming the caloric requirements required for achieving your goal (weight gain/loss).

Advising how to go about losing weight is a really tricky topic. Putting aside the difficulty in determining whether losing weight is actually going to improve your health, what is the best way of going about it whilst making sure that you're both improving your relationship with food, and not creating more rules for yourself?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Unfortunately I would say that no matter what you choose, you are always going to be adding a rule. To lose weight, you must be in a calorie deficit. That in itself is a rule, and hence one needs to be in the right frame of mind to be embarking on that kind of journey. That is why I always encourage addressing the lies we believe about ourselves and food first, and focus on that food relationship as priority number one.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
My current advice is that tracking calories and macros, when combined with intentional learning about calorie and nutrient densities of foods, is going to be the least problematic method. The learning is important, as no one should be counting calories for life, and I believe that our goal should be to aim for intuitive eating as a long term solution. That's how this becomes sustainable.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
